description.text:
Mount for a Vortex Venom red dot sight.

Originally designed for a UK-legal GSG 1911 LBP (Long Barrel Pistol), but should work the same for any of the normal models or clones.

Installation Instructions:

  • Remove the original rear-sight using a hex key.
  • Fit the printed insert into the novak fitting the rear-sight was originally in.
  • Fit the printed mount over the insert, which should rest in the rectangular hole in the base of the mount.
  • Place sight on-top of the mount, the bumps on the mount should fit into the recesses on the bottom of the sight, and the middle holes should line up with the ones in the sight base.
  • Screw 2 M3 screws (about 10mm seems the best length) through the middle holes in the sight and into the mount insert until tight.

As you are screwing directly into the printed insert, they are more or less one-use. My intention is to place some threaded inserts into it so it can be re-used. To be continued ...

Added a slimmed down version with a slightly better fit to the rear of the slide. I've also added one with a charging handle built in.

description.text:
The Prusa I3 Multi-material upgrade comes with parts and directions to build a very nice and functional 4-spool tray. However, it is intended to be placed in the space behind the Prusa printer, or on a shelf above it. I had neither, so the Prusa rack was only useful for parts - like the 16 608 bearings. I took those bearings and a couple of lengths of 20mm V-slot extrusion, a handful of printed parts and built -- a shelf ! OK, it's a "spool holder rack", but that's just a particular kind of shelf, right?

I liked that Prusa's design used the bearings as surfaces for the spool's rims. I'd been using that type of spool holder for several years and it works very well. I had seen similar designs on thingiverse, and have used this concept for the ones I designed for this rack. I have also liberally borrowed and remixed some parts from several makers here (listed below.)

I designed the frame to take up very little table-space, since that's how much I had available. The rack's frame wraps tightly around the back and sides of the Prusa frame and positions the spools directly over the MM extruders' input. With the filament feeding off the back of the rack, it has an almost direct arc to the extruder while leaving plenty of room for the extra filament retracted during color changes.

I've put slot guides on the bottoms of the spool/bearing holders and have left them unconnected to their matching bearing holder so any spool width can be quickly accommodated. The spools are very stable in use and can be re-positioned easily when desired.

I used my spool rack for several weeks without any filament guides and had no problems - it looked a little messy, but worked fine. However, I couldn't leave it at that so I designed a fairly whimsical filament guide - and did it in multiple colors just for fun. I've included both single and multi-color versions, They look a little peculiar, but they work very well and can be easily positioned for each spool.

When I finished the rack, I was reminded of a filling station pump area - especially with spools on top - so I came up with a little multi-color sign to add to that image. The name, "Catnap Motors", (slogan "The Purrfect Ride" -- [a division of "Catnap Industries"]), is that of a pseudo-company I created many years ago. This sign is totally optional, of course, and you can always make something yourself and glue a bit of slot-cover to the back to clip it to the slot.

I have included a cut list for the extrusions, a parts list for the hardware, and a parts list for the printed parts. I've also made a stab at assembly instructions. (See the Thing Files for the .rtf file) Only two of the extrusion pieces must be cut precisely. For the others, a millimeter or two either way won't ruin anything. Note, however, that the pieces are dimensioned to fit the printer and to be cut from two 1500mm V-slot extrusions.

I may have over-engineered the joints - the corner brackets are easy to print and can be decorative as well as functional so I've put one or two at every axis change.

The "Suggested" links in the parts list are just that. You can use the link to see exactly what part I used, and then source the part wherever you want.

I hope this design will inspire one of your own. Aluminum extrusion is easy to work with and is very strong. Lots of parts and accessories are designed for it.

I also hope that this Summary is coherent. I've been playing (and losing) the Thingiverse Expiring Token game for the last few hours.)

I gratefully acknowledge these makers for their designs that I've remixed or borrowed for this project. If the parts work for you, thank them. If they don't, blame me:

V-slot corner bracket and T-bracket are originally from spauda01's D-Bot project: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1001065

V-slot covers resized from sheffdog's near perfect profile: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:832077

Bolts and nuts were generated using mike_mattala's excellent Nut Job library: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:193647

You'll also see in the photos a Raspberry Pi case (totally optional to this build) This is hofftari's Pi case for Prusa (I use the older design for Pi3 for all of my raspis): http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1325370

I've made a simple v-slot mount for that case, but haven't published it, yet. When I do, I'll link to it, here.

I used Simonarri's Miter Razor to clean up the ends of the slot cover strips: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:912051 -- It's not really intended for cutting plastic, but it does.

Notes:

You need to scale this to 1.29 when printing it! I didn't really think over my design well while making it in SolidWorks, so it needs to be scaled to this to work with the bearing it was designed for! The supports for this just need to be on the bed itself. Also, this is probably obvious, but make sure that this is lying flat while printing! It won't print like it is shown in this design. This design doesn't really need infill because it is so thin.

The small ring-thing

There is a small ring around the main hole on the side with the design. This did not print well for me, but taking an Exacto-knife and cutting it off doesn't really hinder the design of it. After printing your two pieces, sandwich the bearing between the two pieces in the main hole. Make sure the design sides face outward. Try out your caps and make sure that everything spins nicely before the next step. Once everything is in order, take everything apart again. Then, use some sort of glue, (I used hot glue, but super glue would probably work better), on one of the pieces, and carefully put the other piece with the bearing in it on top. MAKE SURE you do not get any glue on the bearing or in the bearing. Once this step is finished, add your caps and you are set! I painted mine gold to give it a cool look, but you can do whatever you want with it to make it your own! Honestly, any constructive critiques of the design or advice for my next print would be appreciated!

Basically, I designed this for my Engineering Design Studio 1 class at Rose-Hulman. I was given an assignment to make a fidget spinner, so I thought it was the perfect time to start 3D printing! I made the model in SolidWorks and then figured out the math for the scaling factor. I then just converted it into an stl file, saved it as a g-code, and printed it!

I wanted a Vertuoline pods holder easy to print. Other designs are awesome, but I didn't want to print for 9h to 10h and didn't want to spend too much filament. I printed this one in less than 5h. It is minimalist, does not take too much space and is very stable.

description.text:
I needed a last minute Halloween costume this year. Came up with this remix of Devin Stawicki's iPhone 5 case at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:85301 with an adapter to attach it to a $3 Harbor Freight Swivel Lens Headlamp found at https://www.harborfreight.com/headlamp-with-swivel-lens-45807.html.

Once printed, insert your iPhone 5 into the case. It's a snug fit. You will then need to remove the bolt that attaches the lamp to the base of the Harbor Freight headlamp assembly. Reassemble with the original bolt, using your new iPhone case in place of the headlamp part. Be careful not to over-tighten the bolt or it may place too much stress on the part. With just enough tightness, your iPhone should be able to flip down with a quick nod of your head, revealing the cyclops within.

To create the cyclops display, the easiest way I found was just to download a few animated gif's of creepy eyeballs and email them to myself. Once you have opened the email and allowed the gif's to download, you can disconnect the phone from wifi (even remove the sim card) and you will still be able to display the animated gif's of eyeballs by opening the email. You can change the cyclops eyeball by simply scrolling up and down, and zooming in and out, within the email to display the different animated eyeball gif's.

Quick video of post trick-or-treating couch lounging cyclops in action

Enjoy and Happy Halloween!

Notes:

Sliced and generated interior supports using Simplify3D. Printed in ABS using 1.75mm Hatchbox black filament. After printing, there was a bad layer separation right down the center of the print,, not sure why. It's my first spool of this filament though so I'm still trying to dial it in.

No time to print another, so after I removed the supports I acetone'd the crap out of the split layer (and the rest of the print for good measure) to ensure layer cohesion. After drying in front of a fan for about an hour, it held up to inserting the phone and has withstood many, many flips up and down today.

The case is a snug fit on an iPhone 5. If printing in ABS, you may consider brushing acetone on the inside of the case to ensure it survives insertion of the phone without separation of the layers. The acetone will tend to bond the layers together, as well as make the entire assembly slightly more flexible. However, I've found the trade-off to be a slight bit of shrinkage and/or warping (depending on the faces you apply the acetone, the amount, and the drying time) as well as slightly less overall strength in the ABS print. Try to apply the acetone in thin, even coats on each surface and allow sufficient drying time in between each series of applications to avoid warping the print. Be sure to allow the entire assembly to dry thoroughly before attempting to insert your phone or attaching your print to the headlamp base.

description.text:
PRINTING

  1. Main Hand (wide with thumb): 20% infill / touching baseplate; PLA
  2. TPU Finger Hinges: 0% infill / no supports / 30 speed / 230 extruder / 70 bed / no fan / 30mm/s retraction; TPU
  3. Finger Plate Remix: 20% infill / touching baseplate / raft; PLA
  4. Fingertip Grips. Two choices; flat or rough: 0% infill / no supports / 30 speed / 230 extruder / 70 bed / no fan / 30mm/s retraction; TPU
  5. Gauntlet: 20% infill / raft / touching baseplate / everywhere supports; PLA
  6. TPU Gauntlet Hinge (x2): 22% infill / no supports / 30 speed / 230 extruder / 70 bed / no fan / 30mm/s retraction; TPU
  7. Tensioner (x5): 20% infill / touching baseplate / brim; PLA

BILL OF MATERIALS

  1. Aqua Net Purple for glass bed adhesion
  2. Hatchbox 1.75mm PLA
  3. SainSmart Small Spool 1.75mm TPU 250g Shore 95A
  4. 3/16 - 1/4" long (4x) "Chicago Fastener" screws. Lowes #137868
  5. 2" Velcro strips. Lowes #184582
  6. Plastic cable cording. Lowes# 86099
  7. 2.5mm machine (wood) screws, brass (5x)
  8. Loctite Epoxy. Lowes #20934
  9. Drill with 3/16" bit.
  10. Scotch Tape.

TO CONSIDER

Gauntlet: do not print flat.
Drill holes BEFORE putting in cords / cleaning out.
The best way to fish the cording through the small hole is to take a piece of FRESH (no break-offs) 1.75mm PLA and work the holes back and forth to get any obstructions cleared. Continue to do this till you can fish the cording through.
ENSURE that TPU finger hinges face UPWARD during installation.
Mirror everything for right hand.
FINGER PLATE and FINGER GRIPS are oriented as THUMB, INDEX, MIDDLE, RING and PINKY fingers.

INSTRUCTIONS:

  1. Print out the MAIN HAND .stl per the instructions above.
  2. Drill out the dimpled holes on the hand (see images) with a 3/16 bit.
  3. Take a piece of fresh / new PLA and work it through the cording holes to clear any obstructions. This'll take many times to make sure it's clear.
  4. Take the "Chicago screws" and screw them in the hand. This is to just keep all parts together for when you put the Velcro in later.
  5. Print out the FINGER PLATE REMIX .stl per the instructions above.
  6. Print out the FINGERTIP GRIPS .stl per the instructions above.
  7. Print out the TPU FINGER HINGES .stl per the instructions above.
  8. Starting with the thumb area on the MAIN HAND, using the exploded graphic, test that the TPU hinges fit in this area. Once satisfied, remove, put your epoxy in the hole and put the hinges back in AS THE HINGE FACES UPWARD; CAUSES THE THUMB TO BE UPWARD.
  9. Assemble the FINGER PLATE REMIX pieces. From left to right (left hand looking at the palm), THUMB, INDEX, MIDDLE, RING and PINKY fingers. Place the TPU finger hinges in each piece to test. Remove, drop some epoxy in and then put the hinges back in. Do this for all fingers AS THE HINGE FACES UPWARD; CAUSES THE FINGER TO BE UPWARD. Place all digits together.
  10. Set the MAIN HAND / TPU HINGES and FINGER PLATE off to the side and allow to dry for 24 hours.
  11. Print out GAUNTLET per instructions above.
  12. Print out TENSIONERS per instructions above.
  13. Print out GAUNTLET HINGES per instructions above.
  14. Run the cording through each digit.
  15. Tie off cording in each fingertip to ensure it's secure / won't move.
  16. Place the TENSIONERS in the GAUNTLET just barely in; this area may be a bit tight.
  17. Tie off the cording to each TENSIONER as everything is without tension / without slack and straight with the GAUNTLET.
  18. GLUE with your epoxy the TPU GAUNTLET HINGE on each side of the GAUNTLET area (where they rest).
  19. Let dry for 24 hours.
  20. Take your 2.5MM Machine (wood) screws and screw in the back of the GAUNTLET / adjusting per tension of each TENSIONER / FINGER.
  21. Emplace the Velcro pieces on the GAUNTLET.
  22. Unscrew the Chicago screws in the MAIN HAND. Place a piece of Velcro in this area, cut a few holes in the Velcro to match up the Chicago screws. Replace / tighten the Chicago screws.
  23. Glue the TPU FINGERPRINT GRIPS in the fingertips (flat or rough - your choice) After gluing, run some Scotch tape around the grips / finger / thumb to hold in place.
  24. Let dry for 24 hours.
  25. Remove Scotch tape from fingers.
  26. Adjust everything as necessary.

comments.text:
• Even for PLA you can put your printer in a box, this will avoid errors of impressions.
  • The 0.6mm head can be a good idea because the precision is made by the steps of the motors, there is no wall less than 1mm in the parts to be printed therefore it accelerate printing without loss of precision.
  • There is no big difference between PLA and ABS in the sound. The ABS sounds a little better in my opinion. In any case, it is better to fill the objects as much as possible.
  • The "Infill" parameter must be as close as 100%. On many FDM printers, there may be print errors beyond 95% because, by recalibrating them, it is possible to go up to 100%. I think the minimum is 75% of Infill for this instrument.
  • Before printing all parts together, it is better to first test only one part. Then you can see if a piece cause an error. If your printer is not very well calibrated it's better to print only one piece at a time.
  • When you have printed your first piece (you can start with leadpipe : piece_19.stl), you have to test if there are air leaks. If there is, the instrument will not be playable.
    By slightly increasing the print temperature, this can help to prevent leakage, but increases the probability of error, so find the right medium. (Only if you have air leaks).
    To test if there are leaks you can clog one side with your hand and blow hard from the other side. If, under pressure, the air does not move, your printer is well calibrated and instrument will produce sound.
    Otherwise it is possible to varnish the inside to remove the leaks but it is more complicated. I have tested acetone vapor inside the complete instrument with really good results. For mouthpieces I have tested aerosol varnish, epoxy glue.
  • For parts junctions, you can welds them with a glue made of ABS and acetone. Even for welding PLA parts it done good results. Epoxy glue, super glue can work too.
  • Curved pipes are okay with a properly calibrated printer (this can work even without supports). If the printer fails to make the part, even if it is cut in half the inside may not be good. It is better to spend a little time setting up the printer correctly in my opinion. You have to play with the settings of the slicer (I've only tested curved pipes with Slic3r but Cura may work too).
    I think it is better to start with the straight trumpet, it's easier to print.
  • And other thing, the bell is harder to print, so you can print it separately (piece_0.stl).

title: 1 m square of asteroid Eros from NEAR

description.text: This is a scan of a 1m x 1m part of the surface of the asteroid Eros taken by NEAR before its terminal touchdown.  I submit it, not as an interesting model, but in response to the asteroid scan request by CosmoWenman.

As you can see, this is a simple heightfield scan from the original image which would be printable if mesh applied to a solid. The challenge was to "upload an original 3D scan of a 1m x 1m area of an asteroid to the Thingiverse and tag it as a derivative of this post. It needs to be scanned directly from the original, from an altitude of no more than 10 meters." No disrespect but I think CosmoWesman is unclear on several concepts. First, there are no images from asteroids from a height of 10 meters. The NEAR project came the closest - this is a scan of a 1m X 1m section of the final descent image taken from a range of 130 meters (http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/planetary/mission/near/descent_images/near_descent_157417198.html), the last actual image and closest image of an asteroid surface. Only Hayabusa has come closer (at 23 m) but it's "lander" did not have imaging equipment, only a laser altimeter (although it did manage to snag and return tiny samples). I'm all for pushing people to try new things and establishing bragging rights contests for more involvement, but this one does not really work since it was not thought out thoroughly. Just take this as a teaching moment - you can get terrains and scans but know what you are asking for.

comments.text: A valiant effort! And no disrespect taken, but I'm well aware that there are no 3D scans of asteroids from a ten meter range... yet. While it's great to see that there are dark-horse contenders out there, I think James Cameron and Planetary Resources are in the lead for collecting my $1 asteroid scan prize, which still stands.

title: E3D V6 Clone Direct Drive Adapter Insert

description.text:
E3D V6 Hotend clone always comes with bowden quick-connect fitting screw-in adapter. This is an issue if you are trying to use it direct drive extruder. Since there's no room for quick-connect adapter in these extruders it has to be unscrewed and short piece of bowden tube inserted into hotened. But it's a problem since there's now nothing to hold PTFE tube straight.
I've searched high and low for adapter, but to my shock there's nothing available.
So I just created a simple one. It screws in using large flat head screwdriver into top of hotend and then you just insert correctly cut PTFE tube...

title: CR-10 E3D Titan Direct Drive Extruder Mount for V6 and Volcano

description.text:
Introduction

I decided to upgrade my extruder and hot end on the CR-10, primarily because I wanted to work with flexibles, but also because the original hotend and extruder are not that great.

This mount attaches the Titan extruder and the V6 hotend directly onto the X carridge, with provision for both a 50mm blower and a BLTouch or similar probe. Having set the firmware up to work with the geared 400 step motor the results I am getting from the printer are hands down the best I have ever had.

Features

  • Accepts E3D Titan Extruder and V6 Hotend.
  • Keeps the nozzle height in the range which can be accommodated by the adjustable bed.
  • If used with an adjustable endstop and the Volcano Fan Duct then the E3D Volcano can be used with this setup. I recommend this one: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2349068
  • Mount and duct for 5051 Blower fan - gives far superior layer cooling to the original fan.
  • Adjustable mount for BLTouch included. Other mounts could be made easily (let me know what you would like)
  • Uses 4mm bowden tube to provide support for the cables running between the frame and the carriage (I simply ran the tube though the nylon overbraid - it works perfectly!)

Printing

I printed this using PETG as I wanted a tough part, but non of it is exposed to really height temperatures so it should be ok to print it from PLA if you wish.

Update 1

I have added a fan duct for the Volcano hot end, which is 8.5mm taller, allowing for the longer head. I have also updated the BL-Touch mount to allow it to drop further so as to work with the volcano.
If you aren't using the BL-Touch or similar probe then remember to change the fixed Z endstop for an adjustable one if you want to use the Volcano, or there won't be enough adjustment in the bed screws to allow for the longer heat block and you will crash the nozzle into the bed!

Update 2

I have now added a mount for an 18mm probe. I don't have such a thing myself so if there is a problem with the mount please tell me what it is and I will correct it!

Update 2.5

Following feedback, I have increased the thickness of the mounting ring for the 18mm probe and moved it further from the hotend.

Update 2.5.1

I have added an image of how the items should be orientated for printing.

description.text:
Edit: Heads up, I goofed on the BOM. Most of the passive component footprints are 0804/0805's and the BOM is all 0402's. I'll update it and re-upload

~Edit 12/15/2017: The 5v voltage regulators on the BOM are not capable of handling +24v input. I'm currently seeking out replacements that will work at higher ratings. I'll update the BOM with the correct size of resistors and caps at the same time.~

BOM has been updated with higher rated components and passives using the proper 0805 footprints
Cus we all know how much fun soldering grains of sand is right? RIGHT?

Rev.D Has been added!

Changes - 1/30/2018:

  • Changed footprint spacing on connectors to allow for use of standard JST enclosed headers
  • Moved fan voltage regulator supply to the control board side of the chain
  • Replaced voltage regulators with a single LM317 @1.5A. Voltage selection is now handled via changing the vref_adj.
  • Replaced PZ20 circuit's LDO with a simpler model with higher input voltage range
  • Added second LDO for dedicated supply to LED's
  • Isolated TH1 from ground plane to address vdroop effecting thermal readings
  • Added grounding vias for edges and isolated areas of ground plane
  • Added decoupling capacitors to power inputs
  • Added "personal touch" graphic

Rev.C has been added!

This design revision includes three improvements:

  • Fixed the hole size for the fan and sensor headers, and gave them a little more space
  • Attempted to clean up and add better labeling
  • Added a set of solderable pads on the edge of the board for pulling Vcc/12v/5v as needed for extra goodies on your print head

This is a concept board design that handles several different things to make managing your extruder head easier.

Features:

  • Precision Piezo Circuit built-in for z-probing. (Big thanks to precisionpiezo.co.uk for making their schematics available to the public!)
  • On-board Voltage Regulators allow the user to select either 5V or 12V fans, even when their printer is using 24V (cus aren't 24v fans just so much harder to find?)
  • LED feedback of each component, including heaters, fans, and touch sense
  • Uses a 24-pin 1mm pitch Flat Flexible Cable for routing between the print head and the control board, allowing for great flexibility and a very clean cable system

Included files are the original cad files designed in PCBWeb Available online for free, an up-to-date BOM using Digikey parts, and Gerber file exports formatted for Seeed Studio Fusion PCB

Please let me know if you have any feedback, or would prefer a different pinout. If you have other feature suggestions, I'd be happy to integrate them!

Update 11/27/2017
I've designed and uploaded a modified X-Carriage that should allow almost complete compatibility with most of the open source print heads out there that are designed for the Prusa/Anet style of printer. The Piezo disk sits in between the print head an the X-Carriage, and is flexed along the Y-axis when the nozzle touches the bed.

description.text:
Add style and/or utility to your Teal Sport drone in seconds with this modular addon system.
In keeping with the quick-swap, modular mentality of the Teal Sport, this 'thing' is a modular addon system that allows for modules to be snapped into the top and bottom of the drone. A few addon modules are shown here, but the possibilities are endless.

Note: I do not own this drone so exact design may need tweaking.

The key to the module addon system is a modified version of the original Teal Sport top cover. The center is removed to create more usable space and reduce weight. Attachment points were added, two external and four internal, to allow anyone to easily create addons that simple snap into the drone's top cover.

description.header: Attachment:  Dev Board and Protective Cage
description.text:
Snap in the development board of your choice using the dev board mount and use your drone as a high speed, high flying development platform. Rumor has it that there is a 5 volt power source onboard, not to mention the drone's batteries. Add accelerometers, weather sensors, GPS, wireless, you name it. Pictured is a Raspberry Pi 0...think flying Wifi scanner!

While two separate addons, the protective cage is a must for your airborne development endeavors. Keep your project protected in the event a rough flight!

Be the top gun at your local airfield with the rocket launcher attachment. This addon attaches two rockets beneath the drone. The rockets shown are based on the 1/4A rocket motor. Launch control can be handled by an onboard microcontroller and some supporting circuitry mounted to the top of the drone using the dev board attachment. Launch could be triggered through an additional radio or by detecting certain movement patterns with an accelerometer. Or use a Raspberry Pi 0 or Onion Omega and trigger a launch via Wifi!

See what you can lift using the lifting hook attachment. The hook is designed to alway hang level when not lifting a load. Simply fly up to your cargo, manuver the hook into position, and fly away. Put that 80mph thrust to good lifting use!

While the lifting hook has your vertical loads under control, the tow hook attachment covers the horizontal loads. Think glider towing and banner pulling. This powerful flier is begging to be an indoor banner puller!
Clip an RCSmoke smoke cartridge onto your drone and show off your manuvers in style!
Want to go back to a near stock drone? Snap in this attachement and you're back where you started, but you're just a couple snaps away from a whole new drone!

This will turn about 60 degrees wait a minute and repeat, another words it not a continuous motion. It is for steeping ejuice.

Print Body with no support with flat side down.
I would not print this at more than 15%. Use a Outline/Perimeter Shell of 4 or more so the motor key will be strong. If using Simplify3D or other programs that allow you to have custom setting per layers, I would use Outline/Perimeter Shell of 4 or more for the first 7mm for the body to increase that motor key hole.

Print Sides with support.

If you notice the picture has the hexagon done wrong, bees would not approve. I fixed it in the body I uploaded.

Parts needed.

Stepper Motor 28BYJ-48 https://www.amazon.com/Elegoo-28BYJ-48-ULN2003-Stepper-Arduino/dp/B01CP18J4A/ref=sr_1_3?ie=UTF8&qid=1509504146&sr=8-3&keywords=28byj-48
Arduino Uno
Code https://github.com/sprenkle/SteepingMixer
2 Pan Head Phillips #4x1/2 in screws
Skateboard/Spinner bearing
Power adapter for Arduino Uno
4 small tie wraps

The stepper motor shown will work with any DIY board(Pi, Feather, Nano, ...), the only thing to watch out for is the powering of the stepper motor board. The Uno is technically underpowered but I have not had any problems when connecting to the 5V output, you might want to power it through another power source or directly to whatever you are powering the controller(Uno) with. If you see problems with it not having enough power to turn, then try connecting the stepper board to a higher powered source. Make sure you connect the grounds to the controlling board(Uno) ground though.

Wiring for Arduino Uno using given code
Stepper Controller to Uno
IN1 - 8
IN2 - 9
IN3 - 10
IN4 - 11
-(ground) to One of the Ground pins
+(Positive) to the 5V pin, not the Vin

description.text:
If you need a desk ornamentation that says, "Yes, I'm a troublemaker, but also I have a home library that smells of rich mahogany and old leather.", look no further than the Trollface Bust. Wind someone up when they come into your office and when you spin this around to face them, they'll be as infuriated as they are impressed by your undeniable classiness.

This is a remix of the great Trollface figure made by Adam Smith. I trimmed the model down to just the head and removed the teeth supports in Meshmixer as they were very tricky to remove cleanly. Thankfully they were also largely unnecessary, you might get some droopy lines but the worst will be behind the rightmost teeth and pretty well hidden inside the mouth. I was completely happy with the small imperfections versus the pain of cleaning it up.I created the base in Sketchup and again went back into Meshmizer to combine them for the final model.

For the one in the photo, I finished it with Rustoleum 2-in-1 Filler Primer and Krylon Fine Texture Stone in the Granite color. The stone texture hides a lot of the layer lines and eliminates the need to do a lot of sanding before painting.

When you need to get something to someone fast, use a Teal Drone with emergency backpack.

This is designed to be an easily printed clip on cover for the Teal Drone. Turning the recreational drone into a valuable tool for farmers, rescue workers, rural workers and lifeguards. This cover easily replaces the original cover, it keeps the drone streamlined as to not effect speed, is designed to use minimal material, to be easily modified and easy to install.

The quickly and easily printed backpack has enough room for a micro defibrillator, a medical kit, sugar for diabetics, a set of keys or other small medical necessities, while keeping to a streamlined profile for speed. The backpack also has an easily removable pin for quick access and the entire backpack can easily be pulled off and replaced with a waiting counterpart.

The original idea was to have speakers and microphone on the drone to allow interaction between the the operator and bystanders, though this would go slightly out side of 'just' a 3d printing project. Also LED's were to be installed to help with visual location, especially along the back face. some of these can be seen in the sketches.

If I knew someone with a Teal Drone I would print them one:)

title: Wanhao i3 Plus extruder block designer's placeholder

description.text:
This is a placeholder object for 3D designers. It was rough-modelled based on the critical dimensions of a real-world object. It has three intended uses:

  1. A virtual placeholder. Import it into your CAD program and then build around it. This helps you position features like mounting holes, and allows you to visualise the design as a completed whole.
  2. A subtractive tool. Use it to subtract a space from another shape, like making a knife sheath by using a model of a knife blade to cut a hole into a block.
  3. A measurement aid. Open the STL in Netfabb Basic and make virtual measurements from it.
  4. A physical placeholder. If you design a holder for your phone, for example, you can print a placeholder for testing instead of risking your phone.

This is a model of the extruder block from my Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus. I used it to design the GUST i3 print cooler. Files included are:

  1. The X axis bracket that holds everything to the rails.
  2. A Micro Swiss hot end and cooling block
  3. The stepper motor, extruder gear, heatsink, and cooling fan for the extruder block
  4. A file that incorporates all of the above.

Each comes in the following file formats:

  • Fusion 360 project (.f3d)
  • Standard for the Exchange of Product model data (.step)
  • Stereolithography (.stl)

This is a re-mix of the thing:2204847 by arunasv. The major difference is that it is intended to mount the long surface to the Z-frame with two screws to mount to the Z-Axis Motor. The intent is to provid lateral support for the motor so that the mass of the gantry, extruder, and hot end do not cause the motor to rotate out of alignment. In tinkercad I eliminated the span to the far side of the z-axis motor, and added a 2mm layer along the Z-axis to provide that support.

There are other ways of doing this, including using the original part, adding support up the z-axis that gets secured higher, however I was looking to be able to lift the motor to get a little bit of extra Z height, and if you go much taller than the part uploaded by arunasv, you start running into the Z-axis range of motion.

i wanted this to take images of grain towers to bring the building lines back into square because of there height

and i wanted nikon mount lenses so i can still use these lenses on my camera with out adapters

this does not work with my wide angle 17-55 zoom lense

my best knolage about this is that you have to use a full frame lens from older 35mm film cameras and it has to be a fixed focal length with a aperture ring

i am looking at nikon 50mm 35mm film camera lenses on ebay i will be ordering one in the next week or so and update on if this works or not

here is this nikon shift tilt adapter with just a few mods
http://www.instructables.com/id/3D-Printed-Tilt-Shift-Macro-Extension-Tube/

what i have fixed is i have added stops to the camera ring to stop at the end lock it into positon and have removed the shift hold bracket because the holes for the screws are to small and not printable ?
so now you use larger plastic screws or more accessible screws

the stl files was originally saved as meters i have converted them back to mm

every thing is tight friction fit so i have left the sizes as is

so make these parts with ABS as you will be sanding and filing parts to fit and expect a lot of time in this PLA is just to hard to file and sand so ABS will shave some of this time off

FYI place the ring spacer with the shinny side up on your camera and then line up the camera side mount to the holes to get a orientation of the ring on the flang then when you have the spacer on the flang lock it onto your camera then put glue on the flang and place it in the upper position then remove in one piece then press them together

other than that go to the instructables web page for any further instructions and information

Use PETG or ABS as it is strong and won't break.
Suitable for X and Y, for Z you need something that provides fine adjustment.

comments.text: Quick follow-up.  I've flown it for about half an hour today with 4 x printed Props.  They are not quite as efficient as store bought props - but not bad.  Battery life reduced by about 30% - though that was probably in part because my motors are a bit too slow, so to fly it needs to run higher throttle.  I'm going to print some 10" props next to see how they compare.  All in, I'm impressed!
comments.author: SimonRafferty

comments.text: Notwithstanding JKeegan's comment - I printed four of these last night and have flown with them on a DJI 450 this morning.  Though they don't produce quite as much lift as the 10x4.5 props I ran before, they work surprisingly well!  I ran one up to full speed (with proper protection) 50W 1000kv and it did not fly apart.  I then tried stopping the prop with a piece of wood - to see how it disintegrated.  It came apart much like any plastic prop.  The pieces slowed down very rapidly with all the pieces landing within 14" of the motor.  It was rather unexciting!

I do a lot of testing with electronics for use with model rockets. To carry them I designed this nosecone.
You can select either 50mm or 80mm inside payload lengths.

For example the file "BT-50_Nosecone_Payload_Base_35mm.stl" is good for use with an 2246 - Estes® Altimeter.

If your printer is well calibrated then you should have no problems in puting the pieces together.

The coupler should be inserted in the nosecone until you measure 18mm in shoulder length. Use CA glue to keep both parts in place.
You might need to drill 3 vent holes in the nosecone. I've designed three dimples into the part for orientation.

Drill two small holes in the payload section and insert a kevlar string as loop. Glue the bottom inside of the payload section with epoxy to hold the kevlar in place and to seal of the end.

Always make sure the nose cone and the payload section have a snug fit!

Enjoy,

Leo
